Miscreant Git Server
====================

The miscreant git server is an OSS, MIT-licensed git server that is
backed entirely by S3/object storage. This makes it easy operationally,
scalable for highly concurrent/agentic workloads, and extremely cost
effective.

Quickstart
----------

Run the server (requires a Rust toolchain for now). By default it listens
on 127.0.0.1:8470 and stores all data under ./miscreant-data:

    cargo run

From any repository push to the server. Unknown repositories are created
on the first push, so there is no setup step:

    git push http://127.0.0.1:8470/miscreant main

Then clone it back from any other directory:

    git clone http://127.0.0.1:8470/miscreant


Why Miscreant?
--------------

Miscreant is for developers building infrastructure like remote
filesystems, sandboxes and harnesses.

Miscreant is a low-level implementation of the git HTTP(S) protocol
that allows for concurrent, transactional access to multiple git
repositories backed by object storage. Unlike using an existing Git
hosting solution like GitHub, miscreant has no rate limits or infrastructure
limitations. It is designed to be extremely cheap to store enormous amounts of
data and serve thousands of concurrent requests.

Miscreant is not a complete developer product, instead the intention is
to serve as an infrastructure component of other solutions such as
remote file systems and sandbox backends.

Why Is Miscreant On GitHub?
---------------------------

As suggested above, miscreant is not a complete developer solution and
requires additional infrastructure (e.g. branch protection, pull request
functionality, authN/Z, etc...). We use GitHub to collaborate on the
development of miscreant and mirror the repository to a self-hosted
miscreant server.

Also, whether we like it or not, GitHub is still the premier destination
for open source hosting. miscreant has no intention of disrupting this for
open source human collaboration.

Architecture Overview
=====================

Miscreant is a single binary rust server built on https://slatedb.io that
speaks the git HTTP(S) protocol:

